body:
@christopherpanderson and I just hit this while migrating an internal project to JUnit5, it seems quite surprising behaviour to have multiple parameters point to the same directory on disk!

The old JUnit4 code used the `TemporaryFolder#newFolder` method:

```java
@Before
public void before() {
  Path dir1 = temporaryFolder.newFolder().toPath();
  Path dir2 = temporaryFolder.newFolder().toPath();
  foo = new Foo(dir1, dir2);
}
```

I _thought_ this could just be replaced by using multiple parameters, but as this issue describes both dir1 and dir2 ended up pointing to the same directory, so the test failed in weird and wonderful ways.

```java
@BeforeEach
public void beforeEach(@TempDir Path dir1, @TempDir Path dir2) { // ðŸŒ¶ðŸŒ¶ðŸŒ¶
  foo = new Foo(dir1, dir2);
}
```

Counter example: which object should be passed in each parameter? Is it going to be an error to not specify an id in this sort of case? How prone is it going to be to using the wrong id?

```java

public class TestClass {

    private Path one;
    public TestClass(@TempDir Path a) {
        this.one = a;
    }

    @BeforeEach
    public void setup(@TempDir Path a, @TempDir Path b) {
        // ...
    }

    @Test
    public void test(@TempDir Path b, @TempDir Path c, @TempDir Path d) {
        // ...
    }

    @AfterEach
    public void teardown(@TempDir Path b) {
        // ...
    }

}
```

I think a test's temporary files should all be confined to a single directory tree. There's no need to have multiple top-level temps.

I would argue that each `@TempDir` would create its own directory, so all seven directories would be different.

*If* you want to re-use the same directory, I would suggest some kind of ID parameter, to support this pattern:

```java
@BeforeEach
public void setUp(@TempDir("a") Path a) {
  // Create a fresh directory with ID "a".
}

@AfterEach
public void tearDown(@TempDir("a") Path a) {
  // As the directory with ID "a" already exists, injects the existing one.
}
```

In contrast, the `@AfterEach` below would create a new directory:

```java
@AfterEach
public void tearDown(@TempDir("b") Path b) {
  // As this is the first mention of ID "b", this creates a fresh directory.
}
```

So, essentially, you would have some map of IDs to directories, with "get or create" semantics. And leaving out `TempDir.value` would simply imply a fresh ID unequal to any other ID.
